= Exercise 1: Origin and Spread of Antarctic Bottom Water
== a) Decribe the formation of Antarctic Bottom Water (AABW)
AABW is mainly formed during formation of sea ice in the southern winter.
As the sea water is cooled below 0°C it sinks below and increses the mixed layer depth (MLD).
The sea ice formation can only start, when the entire mixed layer is cooled to the freezing point of the sea water of $=1.9°C$.
The subsequent freezing process happens relatively fast.
As salt cannot be incorporated into the ice itself, it remains in an increasingly smaller amount of water, forming highly saline brine.
The brine drains out of the ice into the sea and sinks below to the continental shelf.
The salty water on continental shelf comes in contact with the underside of the ice shelf.
Due to the high salinity the ice shelf is melted, freshening the water but also cooling it further down to $-2.1°C$. 
The water is now called ice shelf water and eventually overflows the continental shelf break, falling down the continental shelf.
In the process of flowing downwards it mixes partly with the lower circumpolar deep water achieving its ultimate signature.
